{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-3855].
  {panel}

JIRA 2.6 has a release notes generator. However its design assumes a human will cut/paste the notes somewhere. Many people want to suck in release notes during an automated (eg. Ant-driven) release process, and would like a *single* URL that fetches *just* the release notes in text or HTML format.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-3845].
  {panel}

From a customer:

"*Procedures and policies for issue management* - I was stunned not to find this.  Perhaps it is there, and I've just missed it.  I find no documentation on setting up an environment in which JIRA can be used effectively.  Such a document should include things like "search the bug list before submitting a new one", etc. etc.  All the typical procedures that all your customers will have to put into place.  

Writing this stuff, and making it available (perhaps with a license: you may use this documentation if you have a license for JIRA), would make even more managers want to buy your product - it makes our lives easier.  Of course, we will want to adapt the documentation, but these kinds of guidelines are pretty general and embraced by most that use this kind of product.  I am a strong believer in reuse.  It strikes me that all of your customers are doing something similar here.  Prime refactoring material."

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-3838].
  {panel}

It would be great if you could associate a default issue security level to project components, rather than just at the project level.

We have projects where certain components are classified as "internal", and issues filed against those components should not be client-visible.  While we can set the security level on each issue individually, it's all to easy to forget when entering a new bug.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-3834].
  {panel}

Currently, our JIRA velocity notification templates are full of ghastly constructs like:

${constantsManager.getIssueType($issue.getString("type")).getString("name")}

to access the issue type. We really shouldn't be accessing internal APIs in velocity any more than using scriptlets in JSP.  We should have a wrapper object passed in the velocity context, that exposes each field (incl. custom fields) as simple ${issue.fieldname} properties.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-3822].
  {panel}

We want to generate release notes only for public issues not for internal.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-3786].
  {panel}

It would be nice if JIRA could resend notification emails for a given period.  For instance, when notification mails get dropped by a misconfigured SMTP server or JIRA instance.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-3781].
  {panel}

User list is not alphabetically sorted. Is it sorted randomly?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-3762].
  {panel}

When creating a new bug and you have leads setup for each component and have the default assignment setup to those component leads, if a person creates a new bug and assigned multiple components and the "Assign To" field is set to "Automatic", then the person that is assigned to the bug is the 1st component lead in the list of selected components. We would expect (or want) the "Automatic" assignment to choose the Project Lead since they're in the best position to decide who should fix this issue.
